title: ICE when annotating the return type of a function returning `impl Iterator<Item = &T>` to be `Vec<_>`

labels.name: I-ICE
labels.description: Issue: The compiler panicked, giving an Internal Compilation Error (ICE) ❄️

labels.name: T-compiler
labels.description: Relevant to the compiler team, which will review and decide on the PR/issue.

body:
(Originally triggered by omitting a `.collect()`.) I believe it happens when `Vec` is replaced with another type implementing `FromIterator` too. ### Code Playground: ```Rust struct Foo { inner: Vec, } impl Foo { fn get(&self) -> impl Iterator { self.inner.iter() } } fn main() { let foo: Foo<()> = Foo { inner: Vec::new() }; let vals: Vec<_> = foo.get(); } ``` ### Meta `rustc --version --verbose`: ``` rustc 1.65.0-nightly (20ffea693 2022-08-11) binary: rustc commit-hash: 20ffea6938b5839c390252e07940b99e3b6a889a commit-date: 2022-08-11 host: x86_64-pc-windows-msvc release: 1.65.0-nightly LLVM version: 14.0.6 ``` ### Error output (From playground.) ``` thread 'rustc' panicked at 'index out of bounds: the len is 8 but the index is 9', /cargo/registry/src/github.com-1ecc6299db9ec823/ena-0.14.0/src/snapshot_vec.rs:199:10 ```
